article.headline: LSU 83, Tulane 58
article.story: BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- The last time Glen Davis didn't start a game was in seventh grade. Coming off the bench, Davis, a freshman, had 16 points and 13 rebounds as LSU defeated Tulane 83-58 in the LSU Louisiana Basketball Classic Friday night. "If I start, I start. I know that there is another man in front of me that can fill in at the position and handle his business in the right way. Starting is not a problem," Davis said. "He didn't start tonight but he competed hard and played with a lot of effort throughout," LSU coach John Brady said. "He got some hands on some balls and when Glen gets those cleavers of hands on balls, it's tough to get it away from him. That allowed him to complete plays and get to the free throw line." Never trailing in the game, LSU (1-0) jumped out to an early 11-3 lead three minutes into the game and held a 21-9 lead with 9:56 left in the first half. Despite two nearly four-minute periods without scoring a basket and their best player on the bench with foul trouble, the Tigers held a 34-21 lead at the half. LSU eliminated any chance of a Tulane (0-1) comeback in the second half with a 27-8 run over the first 10 minutes of the half. LSU is now 43-0 when scoring 80 points or more under head coach John Brady. Tac Minor added 13 points and had four assists for the Tigers. Regis Koundjia had 10 points and Antonio Hudson added 11 points and six assists. In limited action due to foul trouble, Brandon Bass had eight points and six rebounds. Tulane was led by Marcus Kinzer's 13 points. He was the only Green Wave player in double-figures. "LSU came out with their athleticism and got up on us and really caused us to play a little timidly offensively," Tulane head coach Sean Finney said. "We just couldn't get on track offensively." LSU advanced to the tournament's championship game against Louisiana Lafayette Sunday.
